-- Japan, China, India, Singapore, Thailand: Asian Bonds, Currency Previews
-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 2010-10-14T21:50:31Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-14/japan-china-india-singapore-thailand-asian-bonds-currency-previews.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  and Finance
Minister Yoshihiko Noda will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Sengoku will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The Bank of Japan holds a quarterly branch managers’
meeting from 9 a.m. in Tokyo. BOJ Governor Masaaki Shirakawa
gives a speech around 9:30 a.m. The branch managers of Osaka,
Nagoya, Sapporo and Fukuoka will brief about their regions’
economies in the afternoon. BOJ Governor Shirakawa will speak at
an annual meeting of Japanese credit unions at 3 p.m. in Tokyo.  The Ministry of Finance will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo
its report on Japanese and foreign investment flows for domestic
and overseas securities during the week ended Oct. 8.  The yield on the 0.8 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 0.875 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 81.45 per dollar at 6:41 a.m. in Tokyo.  China: Property prices in 70 major Chinese cities rose 9.1
percent in September from a year earlier, slowing from a 9.3
percent increase in August, according to China Information News,
the statistics bureau’s newspaper, in a report published today.  Foreign investment in China climbed 5.7 percent in
September from a year earlier after increasing by 1.4 percent in
August, the Ministry of Commerce will say today, according to a
Bloomberg survey of economists.  The yield on the 2.53 percent note due June 2015 was 2.72
percent. The yuan was at 6.6508.  India: Wholesale prices rose 8.5 percent in September from
a year earlier after a similar gain in August, the government
will say today, according to a Bloomberg survey.  The central bank will sell 110 billion rupees ($2.5
billion) of 5-, 10-, and 17-year bonds today.  The yield on the 7.8 percent bond due May 2020 was 8.02
percent. The rupee was at 44.12 per dollar.  Singapore: The government will say today that retail sales
rose 5.9 percent from a year earlier in August after climbing 6
percent in July, according to a Bloomberg survey.  The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due September 2020 was
1.92 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.2961.  Thailand: The central bank will sell 80 billion baht ($2.7
billion) of 14-day bills today.  The yield on the 5.85 percent note due March 2021 was 3.01
percent. The baht was at 29.82.  To contact the reporters on this story:
